-- PRESS DIGEST- Hong Kong - Dec 19
-- 
-- Thu Dec 18, 2014 08:26PM EST
-- None



Dec 19 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  - More Hong Kong people now want legislators to approve the government's electoral reforms next year than before the start of the Occupy Central civil disobedience action for democracy, a poll by Chinese University has found. (http://bit.ly/1C89zyN) - A multibillion-dollar "housing reserve" will be created from the public coffers to help the Housing Authority meet the government's goal of building 290,000 public flats in the next decade, Hong Kong financial secretary John Tsang Chun-wah said. (http://bit.ly/1v5yPkg) - Road injuries have emerged as the third-leading cause of death in China, compared with eighth in the developing world and ahead of a range of cancers, according to a global study in The Lancet medical journal. (http://bit.ly/1x3IlL1)  THE STANDARD - Cheung Kong Holdings Ltd <0001.HK> Executive Director Justin Chiu Kwok-hung expects Hong Kong residential property prices to remain stable next year, with fluctuations likely to be within a 10 percent range. (http://bit.ly/1z23kZR)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  - New World Development Co Ltd <0017.HK> said it had sold more than 3,700 flats so far this year, generating HK$22 billion  ($2.84 billion) in sales, an increase of 47 percent from the previous year.